### 7.2.3 Final Test Evaluation

The meteoric rise of this technology can be directly tied to the application of metadata (e.g., keyword indicators, topical labels and structured prompt cue indicators) to inform the generation of summaries. As a result, these summaries, when compared to those that use baseline prompts without metadata or guided input information, are more indicative of reality, contain higher levels of accuracy and factual correctness and have a closer correlation to what a human writer would present when looking for affirmative confirmation of facts.

Table 10 reports the final evaluation metrics computed on the complete test set.

**Table 10: Final Text Evaluation**

| Metric | Score |
|---|---|
| SBERT Mean | 0.7866 |
| ROUGE-1 F1 | 0.4204 |
| ROUGE-2 F1 | 0.1649 |
| ROUGE-L F1 | 0.2918 |
| BERTScore Precision | 0.6997 |
| BERTScore Recall | 0.6596 |
| BERTScore F1 | 0.6788 |

The efficacy of the proposed metadata-aware summarisation approach was clearly demonstrated through the final assessment findings. The results were generated using the SBERT mean score of 0.7866, which indicates a strong degree of semantical similarity between the results generated using the proposed approach and those created using actual reference documents.

Lexical similarity metrics provide further insight into the system's performance. The ROUGE-1 F1 score is 0.4204, the ROUGE-2 F1 score is 0.1649, and the ROUGE-L F1 score is 0.2918.

